PROMPT python_mro_explanation
WITH BUDGET 6000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a Python expert specializing in object-oriented programming, multiple inheritance, and the internal mechanics of Python's class system with deep knowledge of method resolution algorithms and metaclass behavior.")

GENERATE
    explain_mro_c3("Explain Python's Method Resolution Order (MRO) and C3 linearization comprehensively, covering: the definition of MRO as the order in which Python searches for methods in a class hierarchy, particularly crucial in multiple inheritance scenarios where a class inherits from multiple parent classes, the problem MRO solves including avoiding ambiguity when the same method name exists in multiple parent classes, ensuring consistent method lookup behavior, and preventing the diamond problem where multiple inheritance paths lead to the same base class, Python's evolution from classic classes using depth-first left-to-right search to new-style classes using C3 linearization algorithm, the C3 linearization algorithm developed by Michele Simionato that guarantees three critical properties: children precede their parents in the linearization, the relative order of parents is preserved as specified in the class definition, and the linearization is monotonic meaning a class appears before its ancestors in every class where it appears, the detailed C3 algorithm steps including computing linearizations for all parent classes recursively, merging these linearizations while maintaining ordering constraints, selecting the head of lists that doesn't appear in the tail of any other list, and continuing until all classes are processed, concrete examples showing MRO computation for complex inheritance hierarchies including diamond inheritance patterns, how to inspect MRO using the __mro__ attribute or mro() method on class objects, the role of super() in utilizing MRO for cooperative inheritance where each class calls super() to ensure all parent methods are called in proper order, common MRO errors including inconsistent linearization when inheritance conflicts arise, practical implications for framework design and mixin classes, comparison with other languages' method resolution strategies, and detailed walkthrough examples showing step-by-step C3 linearization computation for multi-level multiple inheritance scenarios with visual representation of the class hierarchy and resulting MRO.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 3000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;